Lord Browne review: university teaching budgets slashed by 80%
Unpopular university courses will be forced to shut under new plans to cut direct state funding for degrees, it has emerged. Direct funding for almost all degrees, with the exception of priority subjects such as science, will be cut. Photo: ALAMY	By Graeme Paton, Education Editor
2:27PM BST 12 Oct 2010
Comments
A radical review of higher education – published on Tuesday – recommends slashing the university teaching grant by 80 per cent. The move would wipe out all Government subsidises for classroom-based subjects such as the arts, humanities and social sciences, it was disclosed. Only strategically important courses, including medicine, science and technology, which are traditionally more expensive to run, will be propped up with state support. In all, the move would cut university teaching budgets from £3.5 billion to just £700 million. The conclusions are likely to be embraced by ministers desperate to find public sector savings to reduce the national debt. Related Articles
Lord Browne review: new 'super quango' to regulate universities
12 Oct 2010
Lord Browne review
12 Oct 2010
Lord Browne's higher education report in full
12 Oct 2010
Profile of former BP chief Lord Browne
11 Oct 2010
University tuition fees could more than double
12 Oct 2010
Lord Browne review: the key points explained
12 Oct 2010
It is believed universities will be forced to impose student tuition fees of around £7,000 a year – more than twice the current rate – just to maintain existing levels of funding. The recommendation – in a report delivered to the Coalition on Tuesday – represents a dramatic shift in the way universities are funded, with the burden falling on individual students instead of the state. Lord Browne, the former head of BP, who led the review, said it would “expose institutions to more competition” and ensure unpopular courses were effectively allowed to fail. Students should also be given more information related to employment prospects to make better course choices, he said. “In our proposals, public spending reductions are made by removing the blanket subsidy that the public currently provides for all courses… and targeting investment in priority areas rather than spreading it thinly,” said the report. “This will expose institutions to more competition as they will no longer get a large block grant year on year regardless of the quality of teaching.”
Lord Browne’s review recommends funding “priority” subjects. This includes sciences, technology, medicine, veterinary science, nursing, other healthcare degrees and certain “strategically important” language courses. In return for the investment, universities must guarantee “minimum levels of quality”, such as a set number of laboratory hours for applied science courses. University departments would be regularly vetted and funding stripped for courses failing to maintain standards. But the move has been criticised by academics who fear subjects such as the social sciences and humanities would be fatally undermined. Dr Robin Jackson, chief executive of the British Academy, said the move would “damage academic excellence and quality of life”. Christine Blower, general secretary of the National Union of Teachers, said: “It’s clear that diversity in our universities will also be affected by a substantial cut in teaching funding and the removal of all financial support from the state for arts, humanities and languages degrees. “Restricting funding to specific courses will also result in a more selective higher education, potentially denying access to certain students creating a decrease rather than an increase in social mobility.”
Mike Neary, professor of teaching and learning at Lincoln University, said: “The withdrawal of funding from these areas demonstrates clearly the anti-intellectual nature of the Coalition government, and its attempt to undermine the meaning and purpose of higher education.” Education News
