Families still find room for a treat
Nigel Chapman tells Amy Wilson why the downturn is good for luxury breaks. 'The downturn is good for luxury breaks.' By Amy Wilson
3:12PM GMT 02 Feb 2013
Comments
When trying to make money from hotels in a recession, it helps if you have done it before.
A year ago, Nigel Chapman bought back the hotel chain he set up from Von Essen, which collapsed in 2011. He also bought three more hotels with the backing of property-focused private equity fund, Patron Capital.
Rather than feeling overwhelmed as he tries to increase bookings, repair the hotels’ neglected buildings and reputations and show majority shareholder Patron how it is going to make a return, Mr Chapman says he has been through worse.
In 1988 he sold the family house, left a solid career in accountancy and bought Woolley Grange in Wiltshire. With three young children in tow, he and his wife set about turning it from a grand house into a hotel while juggling a large mortgage. The original intention was that Mr Chapman’s brother would run the hotel, but that fell through. Related Articles
