“We opened in May 1989, which wasn’t very auspicious,” he said. “Interest rates were sky-high and it was very, very difficult. Suddenly we found ourselves living there and running it 24/7 with the waterline going over our noses.”
Although they were novices, the Chapmans’ decision to build a luxury hotel that was family-friendly, with a good restaurant and a crèche so parents could have a break, paid off. Word-of-mouth recommendations meant the hotel started filling up, despite the recession of the early 1990s and the setback of the Gulf War.
With Woolley Grange full at weekends, Chapman got together with hotelier Nicholas Dickson and started to build up a small chain of four country house hotels called Luxury Family Hotels. At the same time, the pair set up a chain of city hotels called Alias. The two ventures were funded with a combination of bank debt and a group of as many as 500 shareholders, mainly guests, who put money into the new hotels in return for visiting rights.
Alias was sold to the Asian conglomerate Swire in 2006, with shareholders making back three times their investment, said Chapman. They made a similar return when Von Essen bought Luxury Family Hotels (LFH) for £30m the same year.
Chapman was not looking to sell the family hotels, but the shareholders felt it was an offer they could not refuse. Between 2006 and 2010, he developed a family resort in Portugal, then bought a hotel in Cornwall in 2010 with the intention of building another small chain similar to LFH.
His plans accelerated when Von Essen collapsed and he had the chance to buy back his original business. Chapman declines to confirm what he and Patron Capital paid, but the seven hotels were reportedly sold for £30m. The four hotels from the original chain were sold back for around half what Von Essen had paid for them.
“It was a good time to buy,” said Mr Chapman. “If you’ve got a decent track record and the assets are good, then banks will lend to you.”
Before the financial crisis, hotels were subject to all sorts of fancy financial engineering to leverage their value as property assets. While Mr Chapman was not caught out by that, he maintains that some debt is nothing to be afraid of.
“To get a decent return on your investment you need some debt in there,” he said.
The demands of the families who come for weekend breaks at the hotels have, of course, changed in the past 20 years, but Chapman says many parts of the formula are still the same.
“Von Essen kindly put in indoor pools and spas, which we couldn’t really afford to do in the 1990s,” he said. “We also now offer more than one sort of eating place. Families want to eat together in the evening, whereas in the past the kids had tea and the parents went for dinner once the children were in bed.”
There are also playrooms for older children with Wiis and other computer games. But the most popular activity at Ickworth, part of a former stately home in Suffolk, is still bicycle riding.
“It’s about giving people respite from working hard, and providing the right things so both they and their kids have a good time,” said Mr Chapman.
As well as refurbishing tired-looking rooms and public areas, he and his staff have overhauled sales and marketing, which he said had suffered from a lack of investment.
“We’ve missed six years of families having children, who don’t know anything about us,” he said. Reviews from journalists, advertising on sites such as Mumsnet and link-ups with complementary brands such as Trunki have all helped to revive the reputation of the hotels in the past year. As a result, revenue this year is expected to be 25pc higher than last year and the hotels are trading profitably, although not yet at the levels they were before the sale in 2006. “As we learned the last time, if we keep pedalling hard now then we’ll be in a really good position when times are better,” Mr Chapman said. “But it’s not impossible to do well in an economy like this. People do get into a mindset where they deny themselves things, but they can only do it for so long. Eventually they get tired of being miserable and think 'I’m going to do something I want to do’.”
