In praise of Majorca
In response to Nigel Tisdall's article about Majorca, ("Sun, sand and Chopin", January 2), we visited the island last June and found it to be everything we expected and much more. We went to a winery on the north coast and were especially enchanted with Valldemossa where we sampled local brandy, admired the beautiful landscape and enjoyed the laid-back lifestyle. We plan on returning and taking full advantage of all the wonderful experiences that the island has to offer. Adrienne Lee, website comment
Hotel efficiency
I was more than surprised to read of the chaos experienced in the breakfast room at The Grand in Eastbourne (Hotel Watch, January 2). I recently returned from a two-week holiday in the Gran Costa Meloneras Hotel, Gran Canaria, a 1,100 bedroom establishment. Never have I experienced such high standards of efficiency, cleanliness and courtesy. No matter how busy the restaurants were, everyone was served with courtesy and a smile. Crockery, cutlery and tablecloths were spotless and tables were cleared as soon as each course was finished. Being Christmas, this was an extremely busy time of the year yet standards did not drop. Why make the excuse that there were lots of visitors at the Eastbourne hotel for the annual air show? If a hotel is run efficiently, standards should not suffer no matter how full the hotel is.
Stella Bowman, by email
Depressing Dubai My wife and I recently decided to treat ourselves to lunch at the Burj Al Arab hotel. When we arrived at the security gate, the first guard asked us for our hotel and room number (we were staying with friends), the second for our phone number, the third wanted to know if we knew the Asian buffet lunch would cost more than £60 each and the fourth demanded our credit card details. Tiring of this routine, we asked our taxi driver to take us to a more customer friendly restaurant. Dubai is a very depressing place to visit. Each day brought news of further financial calamities and the sky is a forest of stationary tower cranes. Next trip, we'll stop over in Singapore.
Bob Pawsey, by email
Disoriented in Lebanon With reference to Charles Starmer-Smith's article about Lebanon ("Where to go in 2010", January 2), I sense Charles might have enjoyed too much of the nightlife in Beirut in suggesting that Tyre and Sidon are to the north in Lebanon. They are to the south of the country, while Baalbek and the Bekaa Valley are to the east. That said, my wife and I visited Lebanon last year, including most of the places mentioned in the article, and we could only agree with Charles about the vibrancy of the place.
Philip Dew, by email Travel views
